    <div class="container">
        <header class="header">
            <h1>Software Design Models</h1>
            <p class="subtitle">Comprehensive Course Syllabus</p>
        </header>

        <div class="content">
            <section class="section">
                <div class="course-info">
                    <div class="info-card">
                        <h3>Course Title</h3>
                        <p>Software Design Models</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-card">
                        <h3>Credits</h3>
                        <p>3 Credit Hours</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-card">
                        <h3>Prerequisites</h3>
                        <p>Object-Oriented Programming, Data Structures and Algorithms</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-card">
                        <h3>Duration</h3>
                        <p>15 weeks</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section class="section">
                <h2>Course Description</h2>
                <p>This course provides a comprehensive exploration of software design models, patterns, and architectural approaches used in modern software development. Students will learn to analyze, design, and implement software systems using established design principles and patterns while understanding the trade-offs between different modeling approaches.</p>
            </section>

            <section class="section">
                <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
                <div class="objectives">
                    <div class="objective">Understand and apply fundamental software design principles</div>
                    <div class="objective">Identify and implement common design patterns</div>
                    <div class="objective">Analyze software architectures and select appropriate architectural styles</div>
                    <div class="objective">Create and interpret various software design models and diagrams</div>
                    <div class="objective">Evaluate design quality and make informed design decisions</div>
                    <div class="objective">Apply design models to real-world software development projects</div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section class="section">
                <h2>Course Outline</h2>
                <div class="week-schedule">
                    <div class="week">
                        <h4>Week 1-2: Foundations of Software Design</h4>
                        <p>Introduction to software design principles, Design thinking and problem-solving approaches, SOLID principles in depth, Design vs. architecture distinction, Quality attributes and design trade-offs</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="week">
                        <h4>Week 3-4: Design Modeling Fundamentals</h4>
                        <p>UML fundamentals and class diagrams, Sequence and collaboration diagrams, State diagrams and activity diagrams, Use case modeling, Domain modeling techniques</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="week">
                        <h4>Week 5-7: Creational Design Patterns</h4>
                        <p>Singleton pattern, Factory Method and Abstract Factory, Builder pattern, Prototype pattern, Dependency Injection</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="week">
                        <h4>Week 8-10: Structural Design Patterns</h4>
                        <p>Adapter and Facade patterns, Composite and Decorator patterns, Proxy and Bridge patterns, Flyweight pattern, Model-View-Controller (MVC)</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="week">
                        <h4>Week 11-13: Behavioral Design Patterns</h4>
                        <p>Observer and Command patterns, Strategy and State patterns, Template Method and Visitor patterns, Chain of Responsibility, Mediator and Memento patterns</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="week">
                        <h4>Week 14: Architectural Models</h4>
                        <p>Layered architecture, Component-based architecture, Service-oriented architecture (SOA), Microservices architecture, Event-driven architecture</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="week">
                        <h4>Week 15: Advanced Topics and Integration</h4>
                        <p>Anti-patterns and code smells, Refactoring techniques, Design pattern combinations, Modern design trends, Final project presentations</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section class="section">
                <h2>Assessment Methods</h2>
                <div class="assessment-grid">
                    <div class="assessment-item">
                        <span class="percentage">30%</span>
                        <strong>Assignments</strong>
                        <p>Weekly programming exercises applying design patterns</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="assessment-item">
                        <span class="percentage">20%</span>
                        <strong>Midterm Exam</strong>
                        <p>Theoretical knowledge and pattern identification</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="assessment-item">
                        <span class="percentage">25%</span>
                        <strong>Design Project</strong>
                        <p>Semester-long project implementing multiple patterns</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="assessment-item">
                        <span class="percentage">20%</span>
                        <strong>Final Exam</strong>
                        <p>Comprehensive examination</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="assessment-item">
                        <span class="percentage">5%</span>
                        <strong>Participation</strong>
                        <p>Class discussions and peer reviews</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section class="section">
                <h2>Required Materials</h2>
                <ul class="materials-list">
                    <li><strong>Textbook:</strong> "Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software" by Gang of Four</li>
                    <li><strong>Supplementary:</strong> "Clean Architecture" by Robert C. Martin</li>
                    <li><strong>Software:</strong> IDE of choice (IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, or Visual Studio)</li>
                    <li><strong>Tools:</strong> UML modeling software (Lucidchart, Draw.io, or similar)</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="section">
                <h2>Project Requirements</h2>
                <p>Students will work on a semester-long project involving requirements analysis and use case modeling, system architecture design, implementation using at least 5 different design patterns, documentation including UML diagrams, code review and refactoring exercises, and final presentation and demonstration.</p>
            </section>

            <section class="section">
                <h2>Grading Scale</h2>
                <div class="grading-scale">
                    <div class="grade grade-a">A<br>90-100%</div>
                    <div class="grade grade-b">B<br>80-89%</div>
                    <div class="grade grade-c">C<br>70-79%</div>
                    <div class="grade grade-d">D<br>60-69%</div>
                    <div class="grade grade-f">F<br>Below 60%</div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section class="section">
                <h2>Course Policies</h2>
                <div class="policies">
                    <ul>
                        <li>Late assignments will be penalized 10% per day</li>
                        <li>All code must be original work with proper citations</li>
                        <li>Collaboration is encouraged for learning but individual assessment is required</li>
                        <li>Regular attendance is expected for interactive design sessions</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </section>
        </div>
    </div>

    <button class="back-to-top" onclick="scrollToTop()">↑</button>

    <script>
        // Back to top button functionality
        window.addEventListener('scroll', function() {
            const backToTop = document.querySelector('.back-to-top');
            if (window.pageYOffset > 300) {
                backToTop.classList.add('visible');
            } else {
                backToTop.classList.remove('visible');
            }
        });

        function scrollToTop() {
            window.scrollTo({
                top: 0,
                behavior: 'smooth'
            });
        }

        // Add click effects to week items
        document.querySelectorAll('.week').forEach(week => {
            week.addEventListener('click', function() {
                this.style.transform = 'scale(0.98)';
                setTimeout(() => {
                    this.style.transform = 'translateY(-3px)';
                }, 150);
            });
        });

        // Add parallax effect to header
        window.addEventListener('scroll', function() {
            const header = document.querySelector('.header');
            const scrolled = window.pageYOffset;
            header.style.transform = `translateY(${scrolled * 0.5}px)`;
        });

        // Add interactive hover effects for info cards
        document.querySelectorAll('.info-card').forEach(card => {
            card.addEventListener('mouseenter', function() {
                this.style.background = 'linear-gradient(135deg, #e3f2fd, #bbdefb)';
            });
            
            card.addEventListener('mouseleave', function() {
                this.style.background = 'linear-gradient(135deg, #f5f7fa, #c3cfe2)';
            });
        });

        // Add smooth scrolling for any internal links
        document.querySelectorAll('a[href^="#"]').forEach(anchor => {
            anchor.addEventListener('click', function (e) {
                e.preventDefault();
                const target = document.querySelector(this.getAttribute('href'));
                if (target) {
                    target.scrollIntoView({
                        behavior: 'smooth',
                        block: 'start'
                    });
                }
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
